  "prompt": "What are the best Bank robbery movies?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down some of the best bank robbery movies, categorized for different tastes.  I'll give you a good mix of classics, action-packed, suspenseful, and a few modern gems.\n\n**The Classics & Influential:**\n\n*   **The Asphalt Jungle (1950):**  A John Huston masterpiece.  This is often considered *the* blueprint for the heist movie.  It focuses on the planning and execution of a jewel robbery (close enough to bank robbery in spirit), and the diverse characters involved, from the mastermind to the getaway driver.  Noir at its finest.\n\n*   **Rififi (1955):** French crime film. A meticulously planned robbery goes mostly right until a small error ruins everything. Features a legendary, almost silent, extended robbery scene.\n\n*   **Dog Day Afternoon (1975):**  Al Pacino delivers an iconic performance in this based-on-a-true-story thriller.  A bank robbery goes terribly wrong, and the situation escalates into a hostage situation and a media circus.  More character-driven and a commentary on society.\n\n**Action-Packed & Thrilling:**\n\n*   **Heat (1995):** Michael Mann's epic crime saga.  Robert De Niro and Al Pacino face off in a battle of wits and firepower.  The bank robbery scene is legendary for its realism and intensity.  A must-see for any fan of action and crime films.\n\n*   **Point Break (1991):** Patrick Swayze and Keanu Reeves star in this high-octane action film about a group of surfer bank robbers.  Over-the-top but incredibly entertaining.\n\n*   **The Town (2010):** Ben Affleck directs and stars in this Boston-set crime thriller.  A group of professional bank robbers plan one last big score while being pursued by the FBI.  Great action sequences and a compelling story.\n\n**Suspenseful & Clever:**\n\n*   **Inside Man (2006):** Spike Lee directs this intelligent and stylish heist film.  Denzel Washington stars as a detective investigating a seemingly perfect bank robbery.  Lots of twists and turns, and a focus on the psychological aspects of the crime.\n\n*   **The Score (2001):** Robert De Niro, Edward Norton, and Marlon Brando (in his final film role) star in this heist thriller.  An aging thief plans one last score with the help of a young and ambitious accomplice.  Solid performances and a suspenseful plot.\n\n**Modern Takes & Unique Approaches:**\n\n*   **Hell or High Water (2016):**  A neo-Western crime drama about two brothers who rob banks to save their family's ranch.  Great character development, a compelling story, and a strong sense of place.\n\n*   **Baby Driver (2017):** Edgar Wright's stylish and music-driven action film.  Ansel Elgort stars as a getaway driver who relies on music to be the best in the game.  Incredibly inventive and visually stunning.\n\n*   **Den of Thieves (2018):** A gritty and intense crime thriller about a group of elite bank robbers who are targeted by a rogue LAPD unit.  Gerard Butler stars.  This one is less about finesse and more about raw power.\n\n**Honorable Mentions:**\n\n*   **Bonnie and Clyde (1967):**  While not strictly bank robbery focused, it features several bank robberies and is a landmark film in the crime genre.\n*   **Quick Change (1990):** A comedy starring Bill Murray as a bank robber who has a surprisingly hard time getting out of the city.\n*   **Bandits (2001):** Bruce Willis, Billy Bob Thornton, and Cate Blanchett star in this comedic crime film about two bank robbers who kidnap a woman to help them with their heists.\n\n**Key Considerations When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your preferred genre:** Do you want hard-hitting action, clever suspense, or character-driven drama?\n*   **The director:** Some directors (like Michael Mann and Spike Lee) have a distinct style that you might enjoy.\n*   **The cast:** Are you a fan of certain actors?\n\nThis list should give you a solid starting point for exploring the world of bank robbery movies.  Enjoy!\n",
